Generally in flight migratory anthus trivialis can alternate "piiiz"  and the "si" uttered during breeding season near the nest. Here, the "impure" calls seem to be a failed "si"...

recordings.file-name: XC146359-pipit des arbres cris sisisisi 7 et 8 p33 nid du corb 210406 14h44.mp3
recordings.rmk: This is a rare call I have just recorded two or three times in 9 years . Always uttered from the ground, it's constitued by a serie of ascending and then descending notes. And beteween those notes, the bird utters the traditionnal "si" territorial call. Always uttered at the begining of the breeding season, perhaps during the nest construction, it could be a kind of copulating incitement. See also XC146356.

recordings.file-name: XC146350-PIPIT DES ARBRES 2 ind surtout 1,  piiiz posé et décol 2 si 230813_10 9h00.mp3
recordings.rmk: Two birds, but only on is not far from me. Migratory halt. First perched, and then flying off. Two kinds of calls: first traditionnal "piiiz" flight calls. But also at 00:24, two "si" calls, generally uttered near nest, but also in migratory flight. They are so different than the "piiiz" calls than, in migratory flight, it's always difficult to understand they are uttered by the same bird! In 00:20, a strange failed call by the same bird.

recordings.loc: Wijk bij Duurstede, Wijk bij Duurstede, Utrecht
recordings.rmk: Flight calls given during autumn migration. The 3rd and 4th call very much resemble water/rock pipit. After analysis of both calls and comparing with criteria published bij Fijen (Dutch Birding, 2014, 36 (2):87-95) and discussion with the author, the calls fit neither of the two species (incl ssp. *spinoletta*) very well, although it is closer to water than rock pipit based on the criteria. The recording data (Aug 31) is however too early in autumn for a Water Pipit to migrate over NL. Looking at the rhythm at which all calls are given, all recorded calls are presumably given by the same bird, i.e. a Tree Pipit.
Urban area, in my garden. High pass filter 3000Hz 6 dBdB, ZOOM H1.
